  "description": "The posterior is what you believe after seeing the evidence. It is a probability distribution P(H∣E)P(H \\mid E) over hypotheses HH, updated from a prior distribution P(H)P(H) in light of observed evidence EE, using Bayes\u0026rsquo; theorem: P(H∣E)=P(E∣H)⋅P(H)/P(E)P(H \\mid E) = P(E \\mid H) \\cdot P(H) / P(E). The prior captures what you believed before seeing data. The likelihood P(E∣H)P(E \\mid H) captures how well each hypothesis explains the data. The posterior combines both into a single distribution that reflects everything you know.\n",
  "name": "Posterior",
